number, which is not readily
used, was shocking.

23:45.157 --> 23:50.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Miami school
officials say hackers
on the outside have never
successfully broken

23:50.229 --> 23:56.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in and stolen student data. But
the growing
amount of sensitive information
stored electronically

23:56.368 --> 24:01.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has driven lawmakers in at least
15 states
to restrict what companies can
collect and

24:01.907 --> 24:04.243 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
mandate steps to protect it.

24:04.276 --> 24:08.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That heightened security could
put a damper
on digital tools that
personalize learning.

24:08.647 --> 24:18.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Miami, Florida, I'm John
Tulenko of Education
Week reporting for the "PBS
NewsHour."

24:18.457 --> 24:31.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: A new study finds
African-American
patients are often treated
differently when

24:31.203 --> 24:37.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it comes to medicine and care.
The survey
of more than 500 people, 400 of
them medical

24:37.776 --> 24:42.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students, found implicit bias
exists that
may help explain why black
people are sometimes

24:42.614 --> 24:44.750 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
undertreated for pain.

24:44.783 --> 24:49.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Among its findings: Medical
students believed
that African-Americans felt less
pain than

24:49.088 --> 24:52.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
white patients, and even thought
their skin
was thicker.

24:52.458 --> 24:57.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on this perplexing
discovery, we
turn to Dr. David Satin of the
University

24:57.129 --> 25:01.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Minnesota Medical Center, and
Dorothy Roberts
of the university of
Pennsylvania.

25:02.000 --> 25:03.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you both for joining us.

25:03.736 --> 25:08.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Satin, try to describe this
disparity
for me. Why does this exist? And
is it new?

25:08.474 --> 25:10.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. DAVID SATIN, University of
Minnesota Medical
Center: So, Gwen, we have known
that this

25:10.843 --> 25:15.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has been an issue for at least a
couple decades.

25:15.581 --> 25:21.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And every now and then, a study
comes out
that underscores the need for
the field of

25:21.286 --> 25:25.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
medicine, and in particular
medical education,
to do some work and get it
right.

25:25.991 --> 25:31.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is a problem, and it's
been a problem,
and hopefully this study will
spur on more

25:31.163 --> 25:32.798 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
activity.

25:32.831 --> 25:35.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Dorothy Roberts, is
this a medical
problem or a sociological
problem?

25:35.501 --> 25:37.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOROTHY ROBERTS, University of
Pennsylvania:
It's both.

25:37.302 --> 25:41.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what's really important
and fascinating
about the study is that it, for
the first

25:41.540 --> 25:48.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time, links what we have long
known as undertreatment
of pain for black patients with
doctors, or

25:48.814 --> 25:55.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at least medical students' false
beliefs about
biological differences based on
race.

25:55.187 --> 26:00.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those beliefs, as the study
has shown,
are widely held by laypeople as
well. They're

26:00.592 --> 26:08.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
deeply embedded, longstanding
myths about
racial difference, especially
biological differences

26:08.767 --> 26:15.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
between races, which goes back
to the very
concept that race is a
biological difference

26:15.941 --> 26:20.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is widespread in U.S.
society. So it's
sociological, as well as
medical.

26:20.679 --> 26:24.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Dr. Satin, I have to
say the thing
that surprised me the most was
that medical

26:24.750 --> 26:27.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students would think this way,
as well as
laypeople.

26:27.786 --> 26:32.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, are they being taught this?
Is this something
they just bring with them?

26:32.591 --> 26:35.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. DAVID SATIN: Unfortunately,
it's both.

26:35.794 --> 26:40.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, medical students, doctors
are people,
too. We live in society, and
we're exposed

26:40.232 --> 26:47.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the same decade-after-decade
experiences
that determine our beliefs.
However, one of

26:47.306 --> 26:51.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the things one of the medical
student pointed
out to me this morning is that
some of these

26:51.143 --> 26:56.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
false beliefs seem to peak in
second year
-- the second year of medical
school, as students

26:56.148 --> 27:02.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prepare for the boards and have
been memorizing
these associations to answer on
the board

27:02.788 --> 27:04.623 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
exams.

27:04.656 --> 27:09.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: This is a taught
behavior or action.
This is a conscious stereotype,
as well as

27:09.428 --> 27:10.929 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a subconscious one.

27:10.963 --> 27:12.664 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DOROTHY ROBERTS: Absolutely.

27:12.698 --> 27:18.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's deeply rooted and
fundamental to the
way medical education works in
the United

27:18.136 --> 27:24.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States. Students are taught to
notice the
race of their patients, to treat
their patients

27:25.010 --> 27:31.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
differently because of race, and
they're taught
that that's because of
fundamental biological

27:31.817 --> 27:33.919 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
differences between people of
different races.

27:33.952 --> 27:41.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, while this is in part based
on myths and
stereotypes that are widely held
in U.S. society,

27:41.960 --> 27:49.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's also based on the way
students are taught
to treat patients in medical
schools. It requires

27:49.701 --> 27:57.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a radical change in medical
education to address
this, not only addressing
implicit bias, but

27:57.676 --> 28:04.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also changing the way in which
human beings
are treated and differences are
considered

28:04.917 --> 28:06.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in medical education.

28:06.885 --> 28:13.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: David Satin, there
are actually,
to be fair, race, not specific,
exactly, conditions,

28:13.926 --> 28:18.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but medicines and conditions
which are more
likely to affect one race or the
other.

28:18.530 --> 28:23.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. DAVID SATIN: Those are
controversial.
We know that race is actually a
socially constructed

28:23.502 --> 28:29.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
concept. It's not biological,
nor is it genetic,
as we learned from the Human
Genome Project.

28:29.808 --> 28:34.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so while there are some
associations,
those are largely due to social
effects, how

28:34.813 --> 28:40.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're raised. Often, ethnicity
plays a factor.
But they are not biological
effects.

28:40.419 --> 28:42.588 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But environmental
effects, perhaps?

28:42.621 --> 28:47.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOROTHY ROBERTS: Well, I think
that's really
important for medical students
to understand

28:47.459 --> 28:53.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and for their teachers to teach
them is the
difference between health
outcomes, disparate

28:53.332 --> 28:59.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
health outcomes, and the idea
that they're
caused by innate biological
difference, which

28:59.805 --> 29:08.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is false, vs. how racism does
affect health
based on social inequality, not
because of

29:08.981 --> 29:13.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
innate biological or genetic
differences between
the races.

29:13.185 --> 29:19.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this study points out how
dangerous it
is to continue to teach medical
students that

29:19.091 --> 29:25.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
race is a biological category
that produces
these differences in health or
experience

29:25.530 --> 29:30.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of pain based on biological
differences between
the races.

29:30.302 --> 29:33.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, let me ask you
both, this
wasn't a huge study.

29:33.438 --> 29:38.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is 400, 500 people, but
what is your
thinking -- I will start with
you, David Satin

29:38.243 --> 29:42.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- on what the consequences are
of these beliefs
and what should be done about
it?

29:42.414 --> 29:47.386 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DR. DAVID SATIN: So, the
consequences of the
beliefs, we saw in the study, is
part of what

29:47.419 --> 29:51.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
results in unequal treatment.
It's part of
what results in health
disparities.

29:51.556 --> 29:57.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's certainly enough blame
to go around
for how those result, but it's a
component.

29:57.696 --> 30:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what it teaches us is that
we need to
be proactive. I teach the
medical students,

30:02.134 --> 30:07.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
look, it's not your -- it's not
your fault
that you have these implicit
biases. You grew

30:07.739 --> 30:09.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up in society. We all have
these.

30:09.741 --> 30:14.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now that you know, it's your
responsibility.
And we have some interventions
to try to reverse

30:14.312 --> 30:16.248 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

30:16.281 --> 30:21.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOROTHY ROBERTS: But it also
requires a fundamental
change in the way in which
medical education

30:21.253 --> 30:28.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
works, moving away from teaching
students
that the races are different
because of some

30:28.093 --> 30:35.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kind of innate biological
difference that
then causes health disparities,
and instead

30:35.500 --> 30:42.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
showing how racism and other
structural inequities
cause health disparities, and
explore with

30:42.908 --> 30:46.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students how medical practice
can address
those.

30:46.211 --> 30:50.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Dorothy Roberts of
the University
of Pennsylvania, and Dr. David
Satin of the

30:50.849 --> 30:52.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
University of Minnesota Medical
Center, thank
you very much.

30:52.884 --> 30:53.885 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DOROTHY ROBERTS: Thanks, Gwen.

30:53.919 --> 31:08.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. DAVID SATIN: Thank you for
having me.

31:08.567 --> 31:13.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: When ISIS captured
the ancient
city of Palmyra in Syria last
year, they destroyed

31:13.805 --> 31:17.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and looted priceless pieces of
Middle Eastern
history.

31:17.676 --> 31:22.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The city was retaken last week
by Syria's
army, and as the extremists lose
more ground

31:22.514 --> 31:28.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Iraq, archaeologists are
returning to endangered
sites to resecure the past.

31:28.787 --> 31:32.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Jane
Ferguson reports
from Northern Iraq.

31:32.657 --> 31:39.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Badly damaged,
but still standing.
Surveying the harm done to
Palmyra, a drone

31:39.998 --> 31:43.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
flies above the ancient Roman
city.

31:43.335 --> 31:49.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Below, land mines and booby
traps slow the
work of Syrian experts, anxious
to walk amongst

31:50.008 --> 31:56.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these precious ruins again. When
ISIS stormed
into Palmyra nearly a year ago,
many feared

31:56.214 --> 32:03.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the UNESCO World Heritage Site
was lost forever.
The group used it for grisly
execution videos

32:03.255 --> 32:05.857 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and blew up two of its temples.

32:05.891 --> 32:11.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But much it is still intact, to
the relief
of Syria's antiquities chief,
Maamoun Abdulkarim.

32:11.696 --> 32:15.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Maamoun Abdulkarim, Syrian
Antiquities Chief
(through translator): We
expected the worst

32:15.267 --> 32:19.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because of the liberation
fighting, but I
think the nightmare is over. The
panoramic

32:19.404 --> 32:21.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
picture of Palmyra is fine.

32:21.473 --> 32:27.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: When they took
the town, Islamic
State fighters also executed
archaeologist

32:27.412 --> 32:33.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Khaled Asaad, one of the
country's top historical
scholars, who had dedicated most
of his life

32:33.451 --> 32:35.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to preserving Palmyra.

32:35.821 --> 32:40.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The presence of ISIS and other
warring groups
across the Middle East and North
Africa has

32:40.425 --> 32:46.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
seen international
archaeologists abandon
beloved historical sites, from
Libya to Syria

32:46.731 --> 32:50.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and Iraq, fearful for their
security.

32:50.735 --> 32:56.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, with ISIS losing some
territory, there
is hope they may return to a
region that had

32:56.942 --> 33:03.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
become so risky. In Northern
Iraq, a team
from Cambridge University is
back to work,

33:03.248 --> 33:07.519 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
searching for signs of
Neanderthal life in
Shanidar Cave.

33:07.552 --> 33:13.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ISIS never took over this area,
but came deep
enough into Northern Iraq to
cause them to

33:13.558 --> 33:16.228 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
delay their dig.

33:16.261 --> 33:20.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Professor Graeme Barker says the
fighting
across the region has upended
much work in

33:20.565 --> 33:22.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the field.

33:22.434 --> 33:24.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GRAEME BARKER, University of
Cambridge: It
has affected a lot of teams
because they can't

33:24.903 --> 33:31.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get back to places. And I have
worked before
in Libya, and in an area where
now it's impossible

33:31.409 --> 33:38.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to go to. So it's had a huge
impact in terms
of access by foreign teams.

33:38.049 --> 33:42.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: He and his team
were not surprised
to hear that ISIS was destroying
historical

33:42.621 --> 33:45.223 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
artifacts on their rampage
across the region.

33:45.257 --> 33:48.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GRAEME BARKER: Invading armies
have always,
liked, anything to do with
heritage, because

33:48.927 --> 33:53.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
heritage is who we are. We very
much -- we
may not think about it
explicitly, but we

33:53.865 --> 33:56.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are very much rooted in our
past.

33:56.034 --> 34:03.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And archaeology is a highly
political subject,
which therefore comes back to
why it's really

34:03.642 --> 34:06.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
important that these kind of
projects continue.

34:06.578 --> 34:12.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: This dig was
originally meant
to take place in 2014. But it
had to be delayed

34:12.417 --> 34:18.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because ISIS came in and took
over Mosul city,
which is about 150 miles away
from here. That

34:18.657 --> 34:23.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
year, say these archaeologists,
was a write-off
for that sort of work here.

34:23.194 --> 34:27.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But since then, they have come
back twice,
saying that the security is
sufficient for

34:27.732 --> 34:33.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them to continue their work. But
for archaeologists
across the Middle East, security
is now a

34:33.271 --> 34:41.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
major concern, with the rise of
ISIS and other
armed groups targeting
historical sites.

34:41.112 --> 34:46.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mosul was taken over by the
Islamic State
in 2014. The city and its
surrounding areas

34:46.318 --> 34:52.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are rich in antiquities and
historical sites.
In nearby Irbil, ancient pieces
from Mosul

34:52.357 --> 34:56.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rest in the museum, beyond the
reach of the
Islamic State.

34:56.227 --> 35:01.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Abdullah Khorsheed, who
leads the Iraqi
Institute for the Conservation
of Antiquities

35:01.366 --> 35:06.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Heritage, is all too aware
of the damage
that has already been done.

35:06.171 --> 35:08.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. ABDULLAH KHORSHEED, Iraqi
Institute for
the Conservation of Antiquities
and Heritage

35:08.940 --> 35:12.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
(through translator): We have
very strong
evidence of the damage because
we are still

35:12.477 --> 35:16.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in communication with the
officials who have
been working there in Mosul and
because of

35:17.015 --> 35:19.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the images and the videos being
published
throughout social media.

35:19.951 --> 35:25.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are sure that most of these
archaeological
sites have been destroyed by
ISIS. On a daily

35:25.890 --> 35:29.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
basis, we hear that ISIS is
trying to destroy
many such areas.

35:29.694 --> 35:34.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JANE FERGUSON: For
archaeologists like him,
they have mixed feelings about
an imminent

35:35.000 --> 35:41.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
military campaign to retake
Mosul. Getting
ISIS out of its historical sites
may mean

35:41.072 --> 35:42.807 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
damaging them in the process.

35:42.841 --> 35:47.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. ABDULLAH KHORSHEED (through
translator):
When we talk about a war, it
means entire

35:47.879 --> 35:53.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cities will be devastated and
destroyed. This
